<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="63" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,151,1040]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,463,727,752]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Due to it is flatter elytra (
<figureCitation box="[766,850,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 70–75" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1624,1647]" captionTargetBox="[159,1435,197,1611]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[159,1435,197,1611]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 70–75. Sculpture of second elytra intervals of Macroderes species. 70, M. arrowi Janssens, 1939; 71, M. cornutus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 72, M. endroedyi Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005;73, M. foveatus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 74, M. mutilans Kolbe, 1908; 75, M. namakwanus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606196/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kolbe" authorityYear="1908" box="[867,1003,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Macroderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mutilans">
<emphasis box="[867,1003,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">M. mutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[1132,1218,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Macroderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bias">
<emphasis box="[1132,1218,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">M. bias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1880" box="[1276,1429,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Macroderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fornicatus">
<emphasis box="[1276,1429,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">M. fornicatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, nevertheless, it can be easily distinguished from them by impunctate lateral border of pronotum as well as distinct differences in the shape of the internal sac sclerite (
<figureCitation box="[726,810,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–39" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1343,1366]" captionTargetBox="[323,1250,205,1286]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[323,1283,195,1303]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 24–39. Internal sac of aedeagus (24), aedeagus (25) and internal sac sclerite (26-39) of Macroderes species. 26, M. endroedyi Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 27, M. amplior Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 28, M. bias (Olivier, 1789); 29, M. cederbergensis Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 30, M. cornutus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 31, M. foveatus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 32, M. gifboomi Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species; 33, M. leipoldti Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 34, M. mutilans Kolbe, 1908; 35, M. namakwanus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 36, M. oreatus Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 37, M. porselinus Abdalla, new species; 38, M. soleiana Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 39, M. tourtosus Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606178/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="63" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,151,1040]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,506,836,861]" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">Habitat and distribution.</emphasis>
This species was collected from localities confined to the Namaqualand region (
<figureCitation box="[159,234,871,896]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1574,1596]" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution map of Macroderes species." pageId="22" pageNumber="63">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). The area is part from the Succulent Karoo ecoregion which comprises two main bio-geographical domains: The Southern Karoo domain which is inland in 
<collectingCountry box="[800,944,908,933]" name="South Africa" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">South Africa</collectingCountry>
and Namaquland—Namibia domain which stretches from the west cost of 
<collectingCountry box="[508,605,943,968]" name="Namibia" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">Namibia</collectingCountry>
to the west coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[843,989,943,968]" name="South Africa" pageId="22" pageNumber="63">South Africa</collectingCountry>
and includes the areas of Richtersveld, Sandveld, Hardveld and Kamiesberg. The area is semi desert, characterised by a succulent vegetation and winter rainfall.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
